I"c<p>In the short story titled “A Kidnapping”, Greg Egan explores the notion of intellectual property and copyright in a world where cognitive augmentation is a mature discipline. Participants invited to an exhibition are searched for neural implants so that they aren’t able to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-like-a-manuscript">record</a> the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/perception-is-context-dependent">perceived</a> exhibits with high fidelity. This copyright concern highlights a possible conflict between intellectual property law and cognitive augmentation.</p>
